            "body": "> that after the first day you know them and never need this feature again.\r\n\r\nDepends on the use case. If you are browsing, doing mouse only scroll, select and copy can be more handy. That is also muscle memory from everything else in the computer. I understand vim tries to cater to keyboard purists but it still has mouse support. \r\n\r\nThe context menu should be configurable/customizable to limit to a subset of features that too based on context. That is why it is a \"context\" menu and not just a popup.",
