            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "(I don't consider this something that should be a part of the main neovim either)\r\nI personally use \r\nliuchengxu/vim-which-key\r\nand \r\n`noremap <silent><leader> :WhichKey '<Space>'<CR>`\r\nTo enable discoverability of my own leader commands. Sadly afaik there's no way to make whichkey work nicely for neovim built-in commands, but with commands where I find the default to be bad for my workflow this works well.\r\n\r\nFor example I use \r\n```\r\n    noremap <leader>th :tab help<space>\r\n    noremap <silent><leader>tn :tabnew<CR>\r\n    noremap <silent><leader>tx :tabclose<CR>\r\n    noremap <silent><leader>tm :tabmove<space>\r\n    \r\n    \"Window close, split horizontal and split vertical\r\n    noremap <silent><leader>wx <C-W>c\r\n    noremap <silent><leader>wh <C-W>s\r\n    noremap <silent><leader>wv <C-W>v\r\n``` \r\nFor (IMO) better to use tab and window split control hotkeys\r\n\r\nThe way doom-emacs and spacemacs can enable hotkey discoverability for features that are default in vim is also pretty cool. See for example how they show commands one can do after pressing `g`:\r\n\r\n![Screenshot 2020-08-10 at 12 12 35](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13387304/89767556-d947cb80-db02-11ea-9171-ca6cb2c3c669.png)\r\n",
